Infectious diseases in Mauritius and other countries were first detected in Omicron.
Mauritius, Cyprus and Malawi recently reported the first cases of new crown variant Omicron poisoning, Xinhua reported.
Mauritius reported for the first time two cases of Omicron poisoning in the country on 10 July.
One of the infected was a tourist from South Africa who arrived in Mauritius on 27 November, and the other was a Mauritian resident who tested positive for nucleic acid on 30 November after contacting a person who had recently returned from a trip to South Africa.
After hospital isolation treatment, the two infected patients turned negative for nucleic acid and have now returned to their homes.
The Ministry of Health of Cyprus announced on October 10 that it had confirmed for the first time three cases of Omicron poisoning in the country.
All three were students who had returned from a trip abroad earlier this month. All were mildly ill and had not been admitted to hospital for treatment.
To prevent the spread of the poison, the government of Seychelles has stepped up its efforts to prevent and control it.
From December 6 to January 10, passengers aged 12 and over who check in by air will be required to have their nucleic acid tested at the airport at their own expense.
The health ministry also announced on October 10 that it would start vaccinating children aged 5 to 11 with the new Pfizer vaccine.
Malawi's Minister of Health, Konbise Chibanda, said on Sunday that the country had first detected three cases of the poisonous strain of Omicronium.
The country's health ministry sequenced 12 new crown-positive samples collected from November 9 to December 2, and found three cases of infection.
Students are required to complete a full-time apprenticeship at a state-of-the-art vocational school.
Yesterday, a reporter from the city's Education Commission was informed that starting this year, the city will conduct a pilot "modern apprenticeship" training model in 60 secondary vocational schools.
In accordance with the principle of two-way selection, students, schools and enterprises sign tripartite agreements.For students who have reached the age of 16 but have not reached the age of 18, agreements between students, guardians, schools and enterprises must be signed to determine the rights and interests of all parties and the specific positions, teaching contents and rights and interests guaranteed, etc.
The pilot schools shall be encouraged to use the modern apprenticeship system and jointly with cooperating enterprises to carry out pre-labour and post-labour training for enterprise employees.
The pilot schools should reform the talent training model.
Schools and enterprises shall jointly design personnel training programmes and jointly formulate professional teaching standards, curriculum standards, job standards, enterprise master standards, quality monitoring standards and corresponding implementation programmes.
Students are required to complete a six-month internship at the university, which is usually followed by a six-month internship at the college.
According to the characteristics of different specialties, a master can take 2 to 5 apprentices and form a study group to ensure that students master the skills required for each rotation position.
According to the arrangements, from 2016 to August 2019, the city determined 60 city-level modern apprenticeship pilots in three batches, each numbering about 50 people, for a total of about 3,000 students (apprentices).
In accordance with the principle of first piloting and then implementing, and gradually advancing from point to point, we will explore the establishment of a long-term effective mechanism for joint admission, joint training and integrated human development of schools and enterprises, so as to effectively improve students' job skills and improve the student-to-student employment rate and the quality of employment.
Vietnam People's Daily - The Gulf Cooperation Council Meets Common Challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman’s stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait.
It is noteworthy that this is the first visit to Qatar by Crown Prince Mohammed since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed a ban on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to the Gulf diplomatic crisis.
In the midst of the crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt severed diplomatic ties with Qatar and imposed a comprehensive embargo, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations while maintaining close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions severely affected Haiti's internal unity and had a negative impact on the economies of the countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blockaded land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was resolved only at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, when the Gulf states signed an agreement brokered by the United States and Kuwait to move toward “solidarity and stability.”
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are taking the lead in efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors in Qatar.
The Gulf Arab states have resolved their differences and are responding to common challenges by restoring relations with Qatar, a demand that must be united in the interests of all countries and in the interests of regional stability.
During the Saudi Crown Prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land route between the two Gulf neighbours.
A 725-kilometre-long corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate travel and integration of supply chains for citizens of both countries.
Saudi Arabia’s Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and the two countries’ companies have signed 13 memorandums of understanding worth $30 billion.
His visit to the Gulf countries coincided with negotiations between Iran and the world over the rescue of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) on Iran’s nuclear program – an agreement that the Gulf Arab states have condemned for failing to resolve the Iranian missile issue.
The Gulf states have always viewed Iran as a long-term “competitor,” and Iran’s nuclear program as a “threat” to regional security.
The Gulf States believe that it is flawed not to resolve the Iranian missile problem and not to take action to curb Iranian activities in the region.
Saudi Arabia has negotiated directly with Iran against the background that the nuclear talks between the major powers and Iran have failed to satisfy the aspirations of the Gulf states.
Its aim is to contain the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing down the economic growth of the Gulf Cooperation Council countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first summit of the GCC countries since the end of the dispute between some member states and Qatar.
This is an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council to reassess the diplomatic achievements it has made to contribute to the restoration of the unity of the Commonwealth of the Bahamas, while proposing measures to enable its member States to cooperate fully to meet common challenges and contribute to the stability and development of the Gulf States.
