Saudi Arabia's First Biennial Exhibition of Contemporary Art
Saudi Arabia's first contemporary art biennial, the Riyadh JAX Biennial of Contemporary Art, officially opened to the public on December 11 in Riyadh's Jax Art District, northwest of the Saudi capital, with 64 artists from Saudi Arabia, China and elsewhere participating.
This biennial exhibition was jointly organized by the Saudi Dili Biennial Exhibition Foundation and UCCA Yurens Center for Contemporary Art, China, with Fei Yu Tian, curator of UCCA Yurens Center for Contemporary Art, China, serving as artistic director.
According to the exhibition team, the theme of the biennial exhibition is “Touching the stone across the river,” a metaphor for the reform strategies adopted during the period of socio-economic transition, and a reflection of the current state of Saudi social and cultural development.
The two-year exhibition occupies an area of nearly 12,000 square meters, and the exhibition hall spans six interconnected buildings, presenting in six units: Touching the Stone across the River, Inheritance as an Experiment, Marginal Thought, Towards the Public, A Beautiful New World, and On the Spirit of Art.
Among them, 27 Saudi artists accounted for more than 40% of the total number of works in the exhibition, including paintings, installations, and performing arts; 12 Chinese artists also attracted attention, with some artists using recycled materials in innovative ways, such as Xu Bing's 2014 reconstruction of a classic landscape painting with waste materials.
Mr Bakhli, chief executive of the Didier Biennale Foundation, said he hoped the exhibition would build an international dialogue and give global audiences an opportunity to learn about Saudi Arabia's thriving cultural industry and creative community and strengthen interaction.
“The aim of the biennial exhibition is twofold: to engage Saudi contemporary art in global dialogue and to integrate Saudi audiences into the world of contemporary art,” says Fei.
It is understood that a series of lectures will be held during the biannual opening ceremony, with artists, policy makers and opinion leaders from the creative industries discussing topics such as cross-cultural exchange and the development of contemporary art.
