More than 130 Asian-American groups filed a complaint with the U.S. Department of Education and the U.S. Department of Justice on May 23 to protest the discriminatory admissions practices of three prestigious universities in the United States: Yale University, Brown University and Dartmouth College.
The Asian Education League, which brought the complaint, held a press conference in Washington on the same day.
The group's chairman, Zhao Yuqing, said at the conference that the number of Asian applicants who met the admission criteria for top US universities had doubled in the past decade, but the proportion of Asians in the top three US universities remained essentially the same.
Many studies have shown that these institutions “continuously and systematically discriminate against Asian applicants” in their so-called “comprehensive consideration” admissions process.
A 2014 study by scholars such as Sanders showed Asians had the lowest admission rates among all ethnic groups in the three universities, Zhao said.
Data from the U.S. Department of Education also show that among all the Ivy League schools, Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest enrollment rates for Asian students, and Yale and Brown have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian applicants for more than 20 years.
Zhao told Xinhua that they hoped that after submitting the complaint, the U.S. Department of Education and the U.S. Department of Justice would investigate and, after establishing the facts, take measures to stop these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asians in admissions.
They also hoped that the complained universities would take the matter seriously and change their admission policies for Asians.
At present, the three universities complained have not responded.
The Association for Asian Education, founded in 2015, filed a complaint against Harvard University's enrollment discrimination, but the U.S. Department of Education denied the complaint on procedural grounds.
In addition to the Chinese-American groups involved in the complaint, there are also Indian-American, Korean-American, Japanese-American, and Pakistani-American educational groups.
