Don't frighten people on the starting line - Official website
When you go to the bookstore, you can often feel the burst of success books.
Many of today’s successful textbooks preach “best principles” – that is, assuming or implying that you can “do it,” and then telling you “what it is” that you need to do.
It's like saying that we've gone beyond the "how to" part, which is really the most important and fundamental part.
That’s why these books have one thing in common – either do your best at it, or do nothing at all; either 100, or 0; or you climb Mount Tai, or you stay where you are.
This “best principle” is recognized as “excellently correct” by anyone who sees it, but 99% of people are frightened to the finish line.
Because this theory advocates a path of “making up your mind, reinventing yourself, making a big 180-degree shift,” which is precisely what many people’s fatal weaknesses are.
To a man who follows the rules, follows the old, and refuses to change, you must yell in his ear, “You must change.”
The vast majority of people are shy and unable to make up their minds when faced with the word change; or they may have made up their minds to change on the impulse of a moment, and have taken the first step bravely, but often in a short space of time, and then lose the battle in a short space of time.
The echo of Mr. Ma's famous "From Tomorrow onwards" is the most iconic expression of this "universal humanity" classic.
The biggest problem with the “best principles” is that the threshold is too high, often exceeding the limits of ordinary people’s abilities, for the vast majority of people to “wail at the door.”
Perhaps the “second-best principle” is the way to get more ordinary people onto the path to relative success.
At the heart of the “second-best principle” is “reducing the threshold” – which encourages a “win-win-win” theory, that is, if you can’t do 100, you can only do one: because one is always greater than zero; and if you can’t climb Mount Tai, you can only climb the little dunes at your doorstep, because that’s always better than walking.
Anyway, as long as you do something, it's always better than not doing it.
Because the threshold has been greatly reduced, there is much more chance that ordinary people will stick to it, and the probability of success will increase as long as everything sticks to it.
The road to success is just a little longer, following the “second-best principle.”
In short, the “best principle,” while ostensibly a banner of success for all, ultimately inspires few, if any, people; and the “second-best principle,” in effect, inspires more people and benefits them as much as possible.
